# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: brachiopod
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] Along with the 28S and 5.8S rRNA in eukaryotes, the **18S rRNA** was early identified as integral structural element of ribosomes which were first characterized by their sedimentation properties and named according to measured Svedberg units.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] Given its ubiquitous presence in eukaryotic life, the evolution of the 18S rRNA was soon proposed as marker for phylogenetic studies to resolve the evolution of eukaryotes.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] The **18S ribosomal RNA** is the structural RNA of the small subunit in the eukaryotic cytoplasmic ribosome.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] The genomic sequence of the 18S rRNA is organized in a group with the 28S and 5.8S rRNA, separated and flanked by the ITS-1, ITS-2 and ETS spacer regions.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] These regions of ribosomal DNA (rDNA) are present with several hundred copies in the active genome, clustered in nucleolus organizer regions (NORs).
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] In ribosome biogenesis, these genes are transcribed together by the RNA polymerase I and are processed in the nucleolus structure of the nucleus.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] The length of the 18S rRNA varies considerably in the eukaryotic phylogenetic tree, corresponding to a range of 16S-19S in Svedberg units, with the average length commonly given as around 2000 nucleotides.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] The 18S rRNA of humans has a length of 1869 nucleotides.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] The universal presence of the **18S rRNA** in eukaryotes and generally high degree of conservation in evolution allow the construction of universal primers for DNA amplification by polymerase chain reaction.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] The possible applications mirror molecular methods involving 16S rRNA of prokaryotes.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] Primers binding in highly conserved regions of the 18S rRNA are an important marker for biodiversity screening, allowing the amplification of unspecified or random targets from environmental samples as well as uncharacterized specimens from collections for DNA sequencing.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] Subsequent sequence alignment covering the less strictly conserved segments then allows the assignment of a sample to biologic clades.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] In the case of 18S rRNA, retrieval of DNA is improved by the abundance of repeating sequences of the rDNA within eukaryotic cells, promoting the sensitivity of the analysis.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] Multiple properties of the genomic sequence of the 18S rRNA have established it as an important marker gene for large-scale phylogenetic analysis and the reconstruction of the metazoan tree of life.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] The integral role in formation and function of the ribosome is a key cause for its omnipresence in eukaryotic life.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] Meanwhile, the gene maintains a high degree of conservation under a persistent selective pressure in all living beings, highlighting its potential for comparison between distantly related clades.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] Early studies utilizing the 18S rRNA sequence constructed the first large-scale phylogenetic trees of the metazoa.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] Evidence from further studies led to the creation of several important clades, such as the Ecdysozoa and Lophotrochozoa.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] During the latter part of the 2000s, and with increased numbers of taxa included into molecular phylogenies, however, two problems became apparent.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] First, there are prevailing sequencing impediments in representatives of certain taxa, such as the mollusk classes Solenogastres and Tryblidia, selected bivalve taxa, and the enigmatic crustacean class Remipedia.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] Failure to obtain 18S sequences of single taxa is considered a common phenomenon but is rarely ever reported.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] Secondly, in contrast to initially high hopes, 18S cannot resolve nodes at all taxonomic levels and its efficacy varies considerably among clades.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] This has been discussed as an effect of rapid ancient radiation within short periods.
[src:brachiopod/18s-rrna] Multigene analyses are currently thought to give more reliable results for tracing deep branching events in Metazoa but 18S still is extensively used in phylogenetic analyses.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:brachiopod/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:brachiopod/acidobacteriota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The **acorn worms** or **Enteropneusta** are a hemichordate class of invertebrates.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The closest non-hemichordate relatives of the Enteropneusta are the echinoderms.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] There are 111 known species of acorn worm in the world, the main species for research being *Saccoglossus kowalevskii*.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Two families—Harrimaniidae and Ptychoderidae—separated at least 370 million years ago.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Until recently, it was thought that all species lived in the sediment on the seabed, subsisting as deposit feeders or suspension feeders.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] However, the early 21st century has seen the description of a new family, the Torquaratoridae, evidently limited to the deep sea, in which most of the species crawl on the surface of the ocean bottom and alternatively rise into the water column, evidently to drift to new foraging sites.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] It is assumed that the ancestors of acorn worms used to live in tubes like their relatives Pterobranchia, but that they eventually started to live a safer and more sheltered existence in sediment burrows instead.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The body length normally range from 2 centimetres (0.79 in) to 2.5 metres (8 ft 2 in) (*Balanoglossus gigas*), but one species, *Meioglossus psammophilus*, only reach 0.6 millimetres (0.024 in).
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Due to secretions containing elements like iodine, the animals have an iodoform-like smell.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Most acorn worms range from 9 to 45 centimetres (3.5 to 17.7 in) in length, with the largest species, *Balanoglossus gigas*, reaching 1.5 metres (5 ft) or more.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The body is made up of three main parts: an acorn-shaped proboscis, a short fleshy collar that lies behind it, and a long, worm-like trunk.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The creature's mouth is located at the collar behind the proboscis.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The skin is covered with cilia as well as glands that secrete mucus.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Some produce a bromide compound that gives them a medicinal smell and might protect them from bacteria and predators.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Acorn worms move only sluggishly, using ciliary action and peristalsis of the proboscis.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Many acorn worms are detritus feeders, eating sand or mud and extracting organic detritus.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Others feed on organic material suspended in the water, which they can draw into the mouth using the cilia on the gill bars.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Research indicates that the rate of feeding of acorn worms that are detritus feeders is dependent on food availability and flow rate.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] A groove lined with cilia lies just in front of the mouth and directs suspended food into the mouth and may allow the animal to taste.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The mouth cavity is tubular, with a narrow diverticulum or stomochord extending up into the proboscis.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] This diverticulum was once thought to be homologous with the notochord of chordates, hence the name "hemichordate" for the phylum.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The mouth opens posteriorly into a pharynx with a row of gill slits along either side.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The remainder of the digestive system consists of an oesophagus and intestine; there is no stomach.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] In some families there are openings in the dorsal surface of the oesophagus connecting to the external surface, through which water from the food can be squeezed, helping to concentrate it.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Digestion occurs in the intestine, with food material being pulled through by cilia, rather than by muscular action.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Acorn worms breathe by drawing in oxygenated water through their mouth.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The water then flows out the animal's gills which are on its trunk.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Thus, the acorn worm breathes about the same way as fish.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have an open circulatory system, in which the blood flows through the tissues sinuses.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] A dorsal blood vessel in the mesentery above the gut delivers blood to a sinus in the proboscis that contains a muscular sac acting as a heart.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Unlike the hearts of most other animals, however, this structure is a closed fluid-filled vesicle whose interior does not connect directly to the blood system.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Nonetheless, it does regularly pulsate, helping to push blood through the surrounding sinuses.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] From the central sinus in the collar, blood flows to a complex series of sinuses and peritoneal folds in the proboscis.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] This set of structures is referred to as a *glomerulus* and may have an excretory function, since acorn worms otherwise have no defined excretory system.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] From the proboscis, blood flows into a single blood vessel running underneath the digestive tract, from which smaller sinuses supply blood to the trunk, and back into the dorsal vessel.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The blood of acorn worms is colourless and acellular.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Acorn worms continually form new gill slits as they grow in size, with some older individuals of species like *Balanoglossus aurantiacus* having more than a hundred on each side.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The microscopic species *Meioglossus psammophilus* has just a single gill slit.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The gills in some acorn worms have cartilaginous support structures.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Each slit consists of a branchial chamber opening to the pharynx through a U-shaped cleft and to the exterior through a dorso-lateral pore (see diagram below).
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Cilia push water through the slits, maintaining a constant flow.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The tissues surrounding the slits are well supplied with blood sinuses.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] A plexus of nerves lies underneath the skin, and is concentrated into both dorsal and ventral nerve cords.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] While the ventral cord runs only as far as the collar, the dorsal cord reaches into the proboscis, and is partially separated from the epidermis in that region.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] This part of the dorsal nerve cord is often hollow, and may well be homologous with the brain of vertebrates.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] In acorn worms, it seems to be primarily involved with coordinating muscular action of the body during burrowing and crawling.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have no eyes, ears or other special sense organs, except for the ciliary organ in front of the mouth, which appears to be involved in filter feeding and perhaps taste.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] There are, however, numerous nerve endings throughout the skin.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have a Y-shaped nuchal skeleton that starts their proboscis and collar on their ventral side.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The length of the horns of the nuchal skeleton varies between species.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have a circulatory system with a heart that also functions as a kidney.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Acorn worms have gill-like structures that they use for breathing, similar to the gills of primitive fish.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Therefore, acorn worms are sometimes said to be a link between classical invertebrates and vertebrates.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Some also have a postanal tail which may be homologous to the post-anal tail of vertebrates.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] An interesting trait is that its three-section body plan is no longer present in the vertebrates, except for the anatomy of the frontal neural tube, later developed into a brain which is divided into three main parts.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] This means some of the original anatomy of the early chordate ancestors is still present even if it is not always visible.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] One theory is that the three-part body originates from an early common ancestor of all the deuterostomes, and maybe even from a common bilateral ancestor of both the deuterostomes and protostomes.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Studies have shown that the gene expression in the embryo share three of the same signaling centers that shape the brains of all vertebrates, but instead of taking part in the formation of their neural system, they are controlling the development of the different body regions.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The internal relationships within the Enteropneusta are shown below.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The tree is based on 16S +18S rRNA sequence data and phylogenomic studies from multiple sources, with the families Harrimaniidae and Ptychoderidae recovered as non-monophyletic.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Acorn worms are rarely seen by humans because of their lifestyle.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] They live in U-shaped burrows on the sea-bed, from the shoreline down to a depth of 10,000 ft.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The worms lie there with the proboscis sticking out of one opening in the burrow.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Acorn worms are generally slow burrowers.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] To obtain food, many acorn worms swallow sand or mud that contains organic matter and microorganisms in the manner of earthworms (this is known as deposit feeding).
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] At low tide, they stick out their rear ends at the surface and excrete coils of processed sediments (casts).
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Another method that some acorn worms use to obtain food is to collect suspended particles of organic matter and microbes from the water.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Acorn worms are dioecious, having separate biological sexes, although at least some species are also capable of asexual reproduction in the form of fragmentation.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] They have paired gonads, which lie close to the pharynx and release the gametes through a small pore near to the gill slits.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The female lays a large number of eggs embedded in a gelatinous mass of mucus, which are then externally fertilized by the male before water currents break up the mass and disperse the individual eggs.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] In most species, the eggs hatch into planktonic larvae with elongated bodies covered in cilia.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] In some species, these develop directly into adults, but in others, there is a free-swimming intermediate stage referred to as a *tornaria* larva.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] These are very similar in appearance to the bipinnaria larvae of starfishes, with convoluted bands of cilia running around the body.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] Since the embryonic development of the blastula within the egg is also very similar to that of echinoderms, this suggests a close phylogenetic link between the two groups.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] After a number of days or weeks, a groove begins to form around the larval midsection, with the anterior portion eventually destined to become the proboscis, while the remainder forms the collar and trunk.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] The larvae eventually settle down and change into tiny adults to take on the burrowing lifestyle.
[src:brachiopod/acorn-worm] A few species, such as *Saccoglossus kowalevskii*, lack even the planktonic larval stage, hatching directly as miniature adults.
[src:brachiopod/acrotretida] Acrotretides (**Acrotretida**) are an extinct order of linguliform brachiopods in the class Lingulata.
[src:brachiopod/acrotretida] Acrotretida contains 8 families within the sole superfamily **Acrotretoidea.** They lived from the Lower Cambrian to the Middle Devonian, rapidly diversifying during the middle Cambrian.
[src:brachiopod/acrotretida] In the upper Cambrian, linguliforms reached the apex of their diversity: acrotretides and their relatives the lingulides together comprised nearly 70% of brachiopod genera at this time.
[src:brachiopod/acrotretida] Though acrotretides continued to diversify during the Ordovician, their proportional dominance declined, as rhynchonelliforms took on a larger role in brachiopod faunas.
[src:brachiopod/acrotretida] Many acrotretides have a tall and conical ventral valve with a pedicle opening at the apex, while the dorsal valve is convex to a much lesser degree.
[src:brachiopod/acrotretida] Based on preserved muscle scars, the lateral muscles were shifted back and condensed into large bundles of tendons.
[src:brachiopod/acrotretida] These replaced the stout, column-like central muscles, which are present in other linguliforms but apparently absent in acrotretides.
[src:brachiopod/acrotretida] The larval shell, which is retained near the pedicle opening, has a strongly pitted texture.
[src:brachiopod/acrotretida] The adult shell is smooth, with a rounded outline and an organo-phosphatic composition, like other linguliforms.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
[src:brachiopod/actinomycetota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Two major categories are traditionally recognized, **articulate** and **inarticulate** brachiopods.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The word "articulate" is used to describe the tooth-and-groove structures of the valve-hinge which is present in the articulate group, and absent from the inarticulate group.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] This is the leading diagnostic skeletal feature, by which the two main groups can be readily distinguished as fossils.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Articulate brachiopods have toothed hinges and simple, vertically oriented opening and closing muscles.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Conversely, inarticulate brachiopods have weak, untoothed hinges and a more complex system of vertical and oblique (diagonal) muscles used to keep the two valves aligned.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In many brachiopods, a stalk-like pedicle projects from an opening near the hinge of one of the valves, known as the pedicle or ventral valve.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The pedicle, when present, keeps the animal anchored to the seabed but clear of sediment which would obstruct the opening.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopod lifespans range from three to over thirty years.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Ripe gametes (ova or sperm) float from the gonads into the main coelom and then exit into the mantle cavity.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The larvae of inarticulate brachiopods are miniature adults, with lophophores (a feeding organ consisting of an array of tentacles) that enable the larvae to feed and swim for months until the animals become heavy enough to settle to the seabed.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The planktonic larvae of articulate species do not resemble the adults, but rather look like blobs with yolk sacs, and remain among the plankton for only a few days before metamorphosing and leaving the water column.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopods live only in the sea, and most species avoid locations with strong currents or waves.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The larvae of articulate species settle in quickly and form dense populations in well-defined areas while the larvae of inarticulate species swim for up to a month and have wide ranges.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Fish and crustaceans seem to find brachiopod flesh distasteful and seldom attack them.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The word "brachiopod" is formed from the Ancient Greek words brachion ("arm") and podos ("foot").
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] They are often known as "**lamp shells**", since the curved shells of the class Terebratulida resemble pottery oil-lamps.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Although superficially resembling bivalves, brachiopods are not particularly closely related, and evolved their two valved structure independently, an example of convergent evolution.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopods are part of the broader group Lophophorata, alongside Bryozoa and Phoronida, with which they share the characteristic lophophores.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopods are thought to have evolved from "tommotiid" ancestors during the Early Cambrian.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopods were highly diverse during the Paleozoic era, when their diversity exceeded that of bivalves.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Their diversity was strongly affected by the end-Capitanian and end-Permian mass extinction events, from which their diversity would never recover to its former Paleozoic levels, with bivalves subsequently ascending to dominance in marine ecosystems.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Today, there are around 400 living species of brachiopods, in comparison to around 9,200 species of bivalves.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopods now live mainly in cold water and low light.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Among brachiopods, only the lingulids (*Lingula sp.*) have been fished commercially, on a very small scale.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Modern brachiopods range from 1 to 100 millimetres (0.039 to 3.937 in) long, and most species are about 10 to 30 millimetres (0.39 to 1.18 in).
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] *Magellania venosa* is the largest extant species.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The largest brachiopods known—*Gigantoproductus* and *Titanaria*, reaching 30 to 38 centimetres (12 to 15 in) in width—occurred in the upper part of the Lower Carboniferous.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopods have two valves (shell sections), which cover the dorsal (top) and ventral (bottom) surface of the animal, unlike bivalve molluscs whose shells cover the lateral surfaces (sides).
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The valves are unequal in size and structure, with each having its own symmetrical form rather than the two being mirror images of each other.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The formation of brachiopod shells during ontogeny builds on a set of conserved genes, including homeobox genes, that are also used to form the shells of molluscs.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The brachial valve is usually smaller and bears brachia ("arms") on its inner surface.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] These brachia are the origin of the phylum's name, and support the lophophore, used for feeding and respiration.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The pedicle valve is usually larger, and near the hinge it has an opening for the stalk-like pedicle through which most brachiopods attach themselves to the substrate.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Moore, 1952) The brachial and pedicle valves are often called the dorsal and ventral valves, respectively, but some paleontologists regard the terms "dorsal" and "ventral" as irrelevant since they believe that the "ventral" valve was formed by a folding of the upper surface under the body.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The ventral ("lower") valve actually lies above the dorsal ("upper") valve when most brachiopods are oriented in life position.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In many living articulate brachiopod species, both valves are convex, the surfaces often bearing growth lines and/or other ornamentation.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However, inarticulate lingulids, which burrow into the seabed, have valves that are smoother, flatter and of similar size and shape.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Articulate ("jointed") brachiopods have a tooth and socket arrangement by which the pedicle and brachial valves hinge, locking the valves against lateral displacement.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Inarticulate brachiopods have no matching teeth and sockets; their valves are held together only by muscles.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] All brachiopods have adductor muscles that are set on the inside of the pedicle valve and which close the valves by pulling on the part of the brachial valve ahead of the hinge.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] These muscles have both "quick" fibers that close the valves in emergencies and "catch" fibers that are slower but can keep the valves closed for long periods.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Articulate brachiopods open the valves by means of abductor muscles, also known as diductors, which lie further to the rear and pull on the part of the brachial valve behind the hinge.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Inarticulate brachiopods use a different opening mechanism, in which muscles reduce the length of the coelom (main body cavity) and make it bulge outwards, pushing the valves apart.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Both classes open the valves to an angle of about 10 degrees.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The more complex set of muscles employed by inarticulate brachiopods can also operate the valves as scissors, a mechanism that lingulids use to burrow.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Each valve consists of three layers, an outer periostracum made of organic compounds and two biomineralized layers.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Articulate brachiopods have an outermost periostracum made of proteins, a "primary layer" of calcite (a form of calcium carbonate) under that, and innermost a mixture of proteins and calcite.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Inarticulate brachiopod shells have a similar sequence of layers, but their composition is different from that of articulated brachiopods and also varies among the classes of inarticulate brachiopods.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The Terebratulida are an example of brachiopods with a punctate shell structure; the mineralized layers are perforated by tiny open canals of living tissue, extensions of the mantle called caeca, which almost reach the outside of the primary layer.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] These shells can contain half of the animal's living tissue.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Impunctate shells are solid without any tissue inside them.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Pseudopunctate shells have tubercles formed from deformations unfurling along calcite rods.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] They are only known from fossil forms, and were originally mistaken for calcified punctate structures.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Craniids, which have no pedicle and cement themselves directly to hard surfaces, have a periostracum of chitin and mineralized layers of calcite.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Shell growth can be described as holoperipheral, mixoperipheral, or hemiperipheral.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In holoperipheral growth, distinctive of craniids, new material is added at an equal rate all around the margin.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In mixoperipheral growth, found in many living and extinct articulates, new material is added to the posterior region of the shell with an anterior trend, growing towards the other shell.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Hemiperipheral growth, found in lingulids, is similar to mixoperipheral growth but occurs in mostly a flat plate with the shell growing forwards and outwards.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopods, as with molluscs, have an epithelial mantle which secretes and lines the shell, and encloses the internal organs.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The brachiopod body occupies only about one-third of the internal space inside the shell, nearest the hinge.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The rest of the space is lined with the mantle lobes, extensions that enclose a water-filled space in which sits the lophophore.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The coelom (body cavity) extends into each lobe as a network of canals, which carry nutrients to the edges of the mantle.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Relatively new cells in a groove on the edges of the mantle secrete material that extends the periostracum.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] These cells are gradually displaced to the underside of the mantle by more recent cells in the groove, and switch to secreting the mineralized material of the shell valves.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In other words, on the edge of the valve the periostracum is extended first, and then reinforced by extension of the mineralized layers under the periostracum.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In most species the edge of the mantle also bears movable bristles, often called chaetae or setae, that may help defend the animals and may act as sensors.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In some brachiopods groups of chaetae help to channel the flow of water into and out of the mantle cavity.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In most brachiopods, diverticula (hollow extensions) of the mantle penetrate through the mineralized layers of the valves into the periostraca.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The function of these diverticula is uncertain and it is suggested that they may be storage chambers for chemicals such as glycogen, may secrete repellents to deter organisms that stick to the shell or may help in respiration.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Experiments show that a brachiopod's oxygen consumption drops if petroleum jelly is smeared on the shell, clogging the diverticula.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Like bryozoans and phoronids, brachiopods have a lophophore, a crown of tentacles whose cilia (fine hairs) create a water current that enables them to filter food particles out of the water.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However a bryozoan or phoronid lophophore is a ring of tentacles mounted on a single, retracted stalk, while the basic form of the brachiopod lophophore is U-shaped, forming the brachia ("arms") from which the phylum gets its name.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopod lophophores are non-retractable and occupy up to two-thirds of the internal space, in the frontmost area where the valves gape when opened.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] To provide enough filtering capacity in this restricted space, lophophores of larger brachiopods are folded in moderately to very complex shapes—loops and coils are common, and some species' lophophores contort into a shape resembling a hand with the fingers splayed.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In all species the lophophore is supported by cartilage and by a hydrostatic skeleton (in other words, by the pressure of its internal fluid), and the fluid extends into the tentacles.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Some articulate brachiopods also have a brachidium, a calcareous support for the lophophore attached to the inside of the brachial valve, which have led to an extremely reduced lophophoral muscles and the reduction of some brachial nerves.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The tentacles bear cilia (fine mobile hairs) on their edges and along the center.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The beating of the outer cilia drives a water current from the tips of the tentacles to their bases, where it exits.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Food particles that collide with the tentacles are trapped by mucus, and the cilia down the middle drive this mixture to the base of the tentacles.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] A brachial groove runs round the bases of the tentacles, and its own cilia pass food along the groove towards the mouth.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The method used by brachiopods is known as "upstream collecting", as food particles are captured as they enter the field of cilia that creates the feeding current.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] This method is used by the related phoronids and bryozoans, and also by pterobranchs.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Entoprocts use a similar-looking crown of tentacles, but it is solid and the flow runs from bases to tips, forming a "downstream collecting" system that catches food particles as they are about to exit.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Most modern species attach to hard surfaces by means of a cylindrical pedicle ("stalk"), an extension of the body wall.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] This has a chitinous cuticle (non-cellular "skin") and protrudes through an opening in the hinge.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However, some genera have no pedicle, such as the inarticulate *Crania* and the articulate *Lacazella;* they cement the rear of the "pedicle" (ventral) valve to a surface so that the front is slightly inclined up away from the surface.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In these brachiopods, the ventral valve lacks a pedicle opening.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In a few articulate genera such as *Neothyris* and *Anakinetica*, the pedicles wither as the adults grow and finally lie loosely on the surface.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In these genera the shells are thickened and shaped so that the opening of the gaping valves is kept free of the sediment.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Pedicles of inarticulate species are extensions of the main coelom, which houses the internal organs.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] A layer of longitudinal muscles lines the epidermis of the pedicle.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Members of the order Lingulida have long pedicles, which they use to burrow into soft substrates, to raise the shell to the opening of the burrow to feed, and to retract the shell when disturbed.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] A lingulid moves its body up and down the top two-thirds of the burrow, while the remaining third is occupied only by the pedicle, with a bulb on the end that builds a "concrete" anchor.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However, the pedicles of the order Discinida are short and attach to hard surfaces.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The pedicle of articulate brachiopods has no coelom, and its homology is unclear.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] It is constructed from a different part of the larval body, and has a compact core composed of connective tissue.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Muscles at the rear of the body can straighten, bend or even rotate the pedicle.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The far end of the pedicle generally has rootlike extensions or short papillae ("bumps"), which attach to hard surfaces.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However, articulate brachiopods of the genus *Chlidonophora* use a branched pedicle to anchor in sediment.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The pedicle emerges from the pedicle valve, either through a notch in the hinge or, in species where the pedicle valve is longer than the brachial, from a hole where the pedicle valve doubles back to touch the brachial valve.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Some species stand with the front end upwards, while others lie horizontal with the pedicle valve uppermost.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Some early brachiopods—for example strophomenates, kutorginates and obolellates—do not attach using their pedicle, but with an entirely different structure known as the "pedicle sheath", which has no relationship to the pedicle.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] This structure arises from the umbo of the pedicle valve, at the centre of the earliest (metamorphic) shell at the location of the protegulum.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] It is sometimes associated with a fringing plate, the colleplax.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The water flow enters the lophophore from the sides of the open valves and exits at the front of the animal.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In lingulids the entrance and exit channels are formed by groups of chaetae that function as funnels.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In other brachiopods the entry and exit channels are organized by the shape of the lophophore.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The lophophore captures food particles, especially phytoplankton (tiny photosynthetic organisms), and deliver them to the mouth via the brachial grooves along the bases of the tentacles.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The mouth is a tiny slit at the base of the lophophore.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Food passes through the mouth, muscular pharynx ("throat") and oesophagus ("gullet"), all of which are lined with cilia and cells that secrete mucus and digestive enzymes.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The stomach wall has branched ceca ("pouches") where food is digested, mainly within the cells.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Nutrients are transported throughout the coelom, including the mantle lobes, by cilia.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The wastes produced by metabolism are broken into ammonia, which is eliminated by diffusion through the mantle and lophophore.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopods have metanephridia, used by many phyla to excrete ammonia and other dissolved wastes.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However, brachiopods have no sign of the podocytes, which perform the first phase of excretion in this process, and brachiopod metanephridia appear to be used only to emit sperm and ova.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The majority of food consumed by brachiopods is digestible, with very little solid waste produced.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The cilia of the lophophore can change direction to eject isolated particles of indigestible matter.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] If the animal encounters larger lumps of undesired matter, the cilia lining the entry channels pause and the tentacles in contact with the lumps move apart to form large gaps and then slowly use their cilia to dump the lumps onto the lining of the mantle.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] This has its own cilia, which wash the lumps out through the opening between the valves.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] If the lophophore is clogged, the adductors snap the valves sharply, which creates a "sneeze" that clears the obstructions.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In some inarticulate brachiopods the digestive tract is U-shaped and ends with an anus that eliminates solids from the front of the body wall.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Other inarticulate brachiopods and all articulate brachiopods have a curved gut that ends blindly, with no anus.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] These animals bundle solid waste with mucus and periodically "sneeze" it out, using sharp contractions of the gut muscles.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The lophophore and mantle are the only surfaces that absorb oxygen and eliminate carbon dioxide.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Oxygen seems to be distributed by the fluid of the coelom, which is circulated through the mantle and driven either by contractions of the lining of the coelom or by beating of its cilia.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In some species oxygen is partly carried by the respiratory pigment hemerythrin, which is transported in coelomocyte cells.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The maximum oxygen consumption of brachiopods is low, and their minimum requirement is not measurable.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopods also have colorless blood, circulated by a muscular heart lying in the dorsal part of the body above the stomach.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The blood passes through vessels that extend to the front and back of the body, and branch to organs including the lophophore at the front and the gut, muscles, gonads and nephridia at the rear.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The blood circulation seems not to be completely closed, and the coelomic fluid and blood must mix to a degree.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The main function of the blood may be to deliver nutrients.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The "brain" of adult articulates consists of two ganglia, one above and the other below the oesophagus.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Adult inarticulates have only the lower ganglion.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] From the ganglia and the commissures where they join, nerves run to the lophophore, the mantle lobes and the muscles that operate the valves.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The edge of the mantle has probably the greatest concentration of sensors.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Although not directly connected to sensory neurons, the mantle's chaetae probably send tactile signals to receptors in the epidermis of the mantle.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Many brachiopods close their valves if shadows appear above them, but the cells responsible for this are unknown.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Some brachiopods have statocysts, which detect changes in the animals' position.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Lifespans range from 3 to over 30 years.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Adults of most species are of one sex throughout their lives.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The gonads are masses of developing gametes (ova or sperm), and most species have four gonads, two in each valve.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Those of articulates lie in the channels of the mantle lobes, while those of inarticulates lie near the gut.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Ripe gametes float into the main coelom and then exit into the mantle cavity via the metanephridia, which open on either side of the mouth.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Most species release both ova and sperm into the water, but females of some species keep the embryos in brood chambers until the larvae hatch.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] While some animals develop the mouth and anus by deepening the blastopore, a "dent" in the surface of the early embryo, the blastopore of brachiopods closes up, and their mouth and anus develop from new openings.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The larvae of lingulids (Lingulida and Discinida) are planktotrophic, feeding and swimming as plankton for months.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] They resemble miniature adults, with valves, mantle lobes, a pedicle that coils in the mantle cavity, and a small lophophore, which is used for both feeding and swimming.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The larvae of craniids have no pedicle or shell.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] As the shell becomes heavier, the juvenile sinks to the bottom and becomes a sessile adult.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The larvae of articulate species (Craniiformea and Rhynchonelliformea) are lecithotrophic (non‑feeding, living only on yolk), and remain among the plankton for only a few days.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The Rhynchonelliformea larvae have three larval lobes, unlike the Craniiformea which only have two larval lobes.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] This type of larva has a ciliated frontmost lobe that becomes the body and lophophore, a rear lobe that becomes the pedicle, and a mantle like a skirt, with the hem towards the rear.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] On metamorphosing into an adult, the pedicle attaches to a surface, the front lobe develops the lophophore and other organs, and the mantle rolls up over the front lobe and starts to secrete the shell.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In cold seas, brachiopod growth is seasonal and the animals often lose weight in winter.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] These variations in growth often form growth lines in the shells.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Members of some genera have survived for a year in aquaria without food.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopod fossils show great diversity in the morphology of the shells and lophophore, while the modern genera show less diversity but provide soft-bodied characteristics.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Both fossils and extant species have limitations that make it difficult to produce a comprehensive classification of brachiopods based on morphology.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The phylum also has experienced significant convergent evolution and reversals (in which a more recent group seems to have lost a characteristic that is seen in an intermediate group, reverting to a characteristic last seen in an older group).
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Hence some brachiopod taxonomists believe it is premature to define higher levels of classification such as order, and recommend instead a bottom-up approach that identifies genera and then groups these into intermediate groups.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However, other taxonomists believe that some patterns of characteristics are sufficiently stable to make higher-level classifications worthwhile, although there are different views about what the higher-level classifications should be.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] About 330 living species are recognized, grouped into over 100 genera.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The great majority of modern brachiopods are rhynchonelliforms (Articulata).
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Genetic analysis performed since the 1990s has extended the understanding of the relationship between different organisms.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] It is now clear the brachiopods do not belong to the Deuterostomia (such as echinoderms and chordates) as was hypothesized earlier, but should be included in the broad group Protostomia, in a subgroup now called Lophotrochozoa.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Although their adult morphology seems rather different, the nucleotide sequence of the 18S rRNA indicates that the phoronids (horseshoe worms) are the closest relatives of the inarticulate brachiopods, more so than articulate brachiopods.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] For now, the weight of evidence is inconclusive as to the exact relations within the inarticulates.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Consequently, it has been suggested to include horseshoe worms in the Brachiopoda as a class named Phoronata (B.L.Cohen & Weydmann) in addition to the Craniata and Lingulata, within the subphylum Linguliformea.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The other subphylum, Rhynchonelliformea contains only one extant class, which is subdivided into the extant orders Rhynchonellida, Terebratulida and Thecideida.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] This shows the taxonomy of brachiopods down to the order level, including extinct groups, which make up the majority of species.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopods are an entirely marine phylum, with no known freshwater species.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Most species avoid locations with strong currents or waves, and typical sites include rocky overhangs, crevices and caves, steep slopes of continental shelves, and in deep ocean floors.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However, some articulate species attach to kelp or in exceptionally sheltered sites in intertidal zones.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The smallest living brachiopod, *Gwynia*, is only about 1 millimetre (0.039 in) long, and lives in between gravel grains.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Rhynchonelliforms, whose larvae consume only their yolks and settle and develop quickly, are often endemic to an area and form dense populations that can reach thousands per meter.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Young adults often attach to the shells of more mature ones.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] On the other hand, inarticulate brachiopods, whose larva swim for up to a month before settling, have wide ranges.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Members of the discinoid genus *Pelagodiscus* have a cosmopolitan distribution.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopods have a low metabolic rate, between one third and one tenth of that of bivalves.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] While brachiopods were abundant in warm, shallow seas during the Cretaceous period, most of their former niches are now occupied by bivalves, and most now live in cold and low-light conditions.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopod shells occasionally show evidence of damage by predators, and sometimes of subsequent repair.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Fish and crustaceans seem to find brachiopod flesh distasteful.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The fossil record shows that drilling predators like gastropods attacked molluscs and echinoids 10 to 20 times more often than they did brachiopods, suggesting that such predators attacked brachiopods by mistake or when other prey was scarce.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In waters where food is scarce, the snail *Capulus ungaricus* steals food from bivalves, snails, tube worms, and brachiopods.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Among brachiopods only the lingulids have been fished commercially, and only on a very small scale.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] It is mostly the fleshy pedicle that is eaten.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopods seldom settle on artificial surfaces, probably because they are vulnerable to pollution.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] This may make the population of *Coptothyrus adamsi* useful as a measure of environmental conditions around an oil terminal being built in Russia on the shore of the Sea of Japan.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopods are the state fossil of the U.S. state of Kentucky.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Over 12,000 fossil species are recognized, grouped into over 5,000 genera.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] While the largest modern brachiopods are 100 millimetres (3.9 in) long, a few fossils measure up to 200 millimetres (7.9 in) wide.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The earliest confirmed brachiopods have been found in the early Cambrian, inarticulate forms appearing first, followed soon after by articulate forms.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Three unmineralized species have also been found in the Cambrian, and apparently represent two distinct groups that evolved from mineralized ancestors.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The inarticulate *Lingula* is often called a "living fossil", as very similar genera have been found all the way back to the Ordovician.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] On the other hand, articulate brachiopods have produced major diversifications, and suffered severe mass extinctions—but the articulate Rhynchonellida and Terebratulida, the most diverse present-day groups, appeared at the start of the Ordovician and Carboniferous, respectively.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Since 1991 Claus Nielsen has proposed a hypothesis about the development of brachiopods, adapted in 2003 by Cohen and colleagues as a hypothesis about the earliest evolution of brachiopods.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] This "brachiopod fold" hypothesis suggests that brachiopods evolved from an ancestor similar to *Halkieria*, a slug-like animal with "chain mail" on its back and a shell at the front and rear end.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The hypothesis proposes that the first brachiopod converted its shells into a pair of valves by folding the rear part of its body under its front.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However, fossils from 2007 onwards have supported a new interpretation of the Early-Cambrian tommotiids, and a new hypothesis that brachiopods evolved from tommotiids.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The "armor mail" of tommotiids was well-known but not in an assembled form, and it was generally assumed that tommotiids were slug-like animals similar to *Halkieria*, except that tommotiids' armor was made of organophosphatic compounds while that of *Halkieria* was made of calcite.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However, fossils of a new tommotiid, *Eccentrotheca*, showed an assembled mail coat that formed a tube, which would indicate a sessile animal rather than a creeping slug-like one.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] *Eccentrotheca'*s organophosphatic tube resembled that of phoronids, sessile animals that feed by lophophores and are regarded either very close relatives or a sub-group of brachiopods.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] *Paterimitra*, another mostly assembled fossil found in 2008 and described in 2009, had two symmetrical plates at the bottom, like brachiopod valves but not fully enclosing the animal's body.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] At their peak in the Paleozoic, the brachiopods were among the most abundant filter-feeders and reef-builders, and occupied other ecological niches, including swimming in the jet-propulsion style of scallops.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However, after the Permian–Triassic extinction event, informally known as the "Great Dying", brachiopods recovered only a third of their former diversity.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] It was often thought that brachiopods were actually declining in diversity, and that in some way bivalves out-competed them.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] In 2007 Knoll and Bambach concluded that brachiopods were one of several groups that were most vulnerable to the Permian–Triassic extinction, as all had calcareous hard parts (made of calcium carbonate) and had low metabolic rates and weak respiratory systems.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Brachiopod fossils have been useful indicators of climate changes during the Paleozoic era.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] When global temperatures were low, as in much of the Ordovician, the large difference in temperature between equator and poles created different collections of fossils at different latitudes.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] On the other hand, warmer periods, such much of the Silurian, created smaller difference in temperatures, and all seas at the low to middle latitudes were colonized by the same few brachiopod species.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] From about the 1940s to the 1990s, family trees based on embryological and morphological features placed brachiopods among or as a sister group to the deuterostomes. a super-phylum that includes chordates and echinoderms.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Nielsen views the brachiopods and closely related phoronids as affiliated with the deuterostome pterobranchs because their lophophores are driven by one cilium per cell, while those of bryozoans, which he regards as protostomes, have multiple cilia per cell.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However, pterobranchs are hemichordates and probably closely related to echinoderms, and there is no evidence that the latest common ancestor of pterobranchs and other hemichordates or the latest common ancestor of hemichordates and echinoderms was sessile and fed by means of tentacles.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] This conclusion is unanimous among molecular phylogeny studies that use a wide selection of genes: rDNA, Hox genes, mitochondrial protein genes, single nuclear protein genes and sets of nuclear protein genes.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Some combined studies in 2000 and 2001, using both molecular and morphological data, support brachiopods as Lophotrochozoa, while others in 1998 and 2004 concluded that brachiopods were deuterostomes.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The phoronids feed with a lophophore, burrow or encrust on surfaces, and build three-layered tubes made of polysaccharide, possibly chitin, mixed with particles with seabed material.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Traditionally they have been regarded as a separate phylum, but increasingly detailed molecular phylogeny studies between 1997 and 2000 have concluded that phoronids are a sub-group of brachiopods.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However, an analysis in 2005 concluded that phoronids are a sub-group of bryozoans.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] While all molecular phylogeny studies and half the combined studies until 2008 conclude that brachiopods are lophotrochozoans, they could not identify which lophotrochozoan phylum were the closest relatives of brachiopods—except phoronids, which are a sub-group of brachiopods.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] However, in 2008 two analyses found that brachiopods' closest lophotrochozoan relatives were nemertines.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] The authors found this surprising, since nemertines have spiral cleavage in the early stages of cell division and form a trochophore larva, while brachiopods have radial cleavage and a larva that shows no sign of having evolved from a trochophore.
[src:brachiopod/brachiopod] Another study in 2008 also concluded that brachiopods are closely related to nemertines, casting doubt on the idea that brachiopods are part of a clade Lophophorata of lophophore-feeding animals within the lophotrochozoans.
